1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ {The easy choice. In order to give
a check on b4, to swap bishops and to castle on the next move - you don't need
much of a knowledge for that. Seriously speaking - this exchange is perfectly
valid and the fact that Magnus Carlsen played it a couple of times is a good
proof for that.} 5. Qxd2 {I prefer this recapture over the 5.Nbxd2. The
queenside knight will be more active on c3.} O-O (5... d5 6. Nc3 O-O 7. e3 {
will transpose to the same position by different order of moves.}) (5... d6 $6
{is too passive. After} 6. Nc3 {White will push e2-e4 and get a clear
advantage in space.}) (5... b6 {is possible in style of the Queen's Indian
defense.} 6. Nc3 Bb7 7. Qc2 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4] The most challenging, to my mind.}
Bxf3 (7... c5 8. e4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 O-O 10. Be2 Nc6 11. Rd1 $14) 8. gxf3 c5 9.
dxc5 bxc5 10. O-O-O {and later White can use the open "g" file against black's
king.}) 6. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4]} d5 {Black must play this to stop the advance
e2-e4.} 7. e3 Qe7 {The most flexible move. Black keeps the knight on b8 for a
while, intending to develop it either to d7 or to c6 a bit later, according to
the setup that White will choose.} ({An immediate} 7... Nbd7 {is somewhat
passive.} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O Ne4 11. Qc2 Ndf6 12. b4 c6 13. Ne5
Bf5 14. Na4 g6 15. Qb2 a6 16. Rfc1 Re7 17. Nc5 {White achieved a standard
pressure on the queenside and after a long battle brought home a full point in
the clash between two great positional players: 1-0 (85) Karpov, A (2705)
-Andersson, U (2630) London 1984.}) ({The same can be said about 7...b6.} 7...
b6 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7 11. b4 $14 {1/2-1/2 (75) Burmakin,V 
(2526)-Miezis, N (2507) Schwaebisch Gmuend 2017}) 8. cxd5 $1 {I recommend to
determine the center already now.} (8. Rc1 Rd8 9. Qc2 (9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bd3 Nc6
$1 11. Bb5 ({After} 11. h3 Ne4 12. Qe2 Bf5 {Black achieved satisfactory
position in several games.}) 11... Rd6 12. Bxc6 Rxc6 13. Ne5 Re6 14. f3 (14.
O-O b6 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5]}) 14... b6 15. O-O Bb7 {and Black equalized in the
encounter ½-½ (56) Bacrot,E (2713)-Carlsen,M (2837) Biel 2012.}) 9... dxc4
10. Bxc4 c5 11. O-O cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bd7 13. Rfd1 Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 $11 {1/2-1/2 
(62) Nakamura,H (2787)-Carlsen,M (2855) Leuven 2016}) ({After} 8. Bd3 {Black
wins a mini-fight for the tempi.} dxc4 9. Bxc4 c5 10. O-O Rd8 {and equalizes
without many difficulties.}) 8... exd5 9. Bd3 Nc6 {The same idea, as in the
line 8.Rc1, mentioned above. The move is a bit awkward, however.} (9... c6 10.
O-O Nbd7 11. Qc2 {leads to a typical Carlsbad structure. White is slightly
better and should slowly expand his play on the queenside, namely:} Re8 12.
Rab1 Ne4 13. b4 $14) 10. h3 Rd8 11. a3 Ne4 12. Qc2 {The b4 square is now
covered against the black knight jump. Therefore, the move a2-a3 appears to
be more useful than Ra1-c1 in these particular circumstances.} Bf5 13. Bxe4 {
The right moment for this exchange.} ({I had an unsuccessful game in this line
recently:} 13. O-O Rd6 $1 14. Nd2 $6 (14. Ne2 $5) 14... Re8 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16.
Ne2 Qh4 $36 {[%cal Gf5h3] 0-1 (29) Postny,E (2588)-Fedorchuk,S (2621)
Llucmajor 2017}) (13. Ne2 Rd6 14. Nd2 Re8 15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Nxe4 Qxe4 17. Qxe4
Rxe4 18. Rc1 Re7 19. b4 $14 {1/2-1/2 (47) Granda Zuniga,J (2639)-Fedorchuk,S 
(2665) Pamplona 2010}) 13... Bxe4 14. Nxe4 Qxe4 15. Qxe4 dxe4 16. Nd2 Rd5 17.
Ke2 (17. Nxe4 $6 Re8 18. Nc3 Rxd4 $11) 17... Re8 18. Rac1 {White has a long
lasting pressure, as in the correspondence game 1-0 (62) Schwenck,M (2498)
-Bucur,M (2410) ICCF email 2010} *

