1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 c5 {I am skeptical about such
strategically risky moves. But, considering that many grandmasters have
employed it, we have to take this move seriously.} 5. Bxb4 {There is no reason
to refrain from this exchange for White.} cxb4 {So, The black "c" pawn has
moved to b4. White has now good control over the center, as Black is no more
undermining white's central d4 pawn. Has Black achieved something in return?
Well, the pawn on b4 yields Black some space on the queenside and prevents
from white's knight to be developed on its' natural square c3. In some case
Black can use the half-opened "c" file to attack the c4 pawn.} 6. a3 {The main
line is 6.g3, but I recommend to exchange the b4 pawn. Years ago I played 6.g3
as well, but came to a conclusion that the b4 pawn is quite annoying. So, the
move 6.a3 will get rid of it and the "a" file will also get opened for white's
queenside rook. The only drawback is that White spends a tempo to exchange
this pawn. A tempo that could be used for the development of the kingside. But,
I think it's worth it. I had several games in this line and quite satisfied
with my results and arising positions after 6.a3.} bxa3 (6... Qe7 7. e3 b6 8.
Be2 Bb7 9. O-O O-O 10. axb4 Qxb4 11. Nc3 (11. Qd2 $14) 11... d5 12. Ne5 dxc4
13. Nxc4 {with a slight advantage for White. His center is more important than
black's pawn majority on the queenside. 0-1 (41) Burmakin, V (2553)-Hertneck, G 
(2469) Vienna 2016}) (6... Nc6 7. d5 $1 exd5 8. cxd5 Ne7 9. d6 Nc6 10. axb4 Qb6
11. Nc3 Qxb4 12. Qd2 O-O 13. e3 {The pawn on d6 is not a weakness at all, but
a real obstacle for black's further development. White had an advantage in the
game ½-½ (37) Mamedyarov, S (2765)-Fridman, D (2659) Khanty-Mansiysk 2011}) 7.
Rxa3 {The other recapture 7.Nxa3 is also sufficient for a slight advantage. I
give some preference to develop the knight to c3.} (7. Nxa3 O-O 8. e3 d6 9. b4
b6 10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O a6 12. Qb3 $14 {1-0 (43) Laznicka,V (2651)-Castellanos
Rodriguez,R (2495) Monzon 2016}) 7... O-O 8. Nc3 d6 9. e3 Nc6 10. Be2 e5 11.
O-O Bg4 (11... Bf5 12. Qd2 (12. Qb3 $1 {is more aggressive and even stronger.}
b6 13. Rd1 {with a serious advantage for White. It's not easy to find a
suitable square for black's queen. The knight jumps Nc3-b5 or Nc3-d5 are
always in the air. Closing the center by} e4 {also wouldn't solve black's
problems. After} 14. Nd2 {White has good prospects on the queenside, while
black's play is unclear.}) 12... b6 13. Rd1 $14 {1-0 (44) Postny,E (2651)
-Drasko,M (2527) Novi Sad 2009}) 12. h3 Bh5 13. Qd2 (13. Qa4 {is also
promising for White.} Bxf3 14. Bxf3 exd4 15. exd4 Qb6 (15... Nxd4 $6 16. Bxb7
Rb8 17. Qxa7 $16) 16. c5 $1 dxc5 (16... Qxb2 $6 17. Rb1 Qd2 18. Rd1 Qg5 19.
cxd6 Qf4 20. Rb3 $16) 17. Rb3 Qc7 18. dxc5 $14) 13... Re8 14. Rd1 a6 15. dxe5
dxe5 16. g4 $1 ({After} 16. Qe1 $6 Qb6 {draw was agreed in the game Rychagov, A
(2559)-Nikolenko, O (2515) Moscow 2014.}) 16... Bg6 17. Nh4 Qxd2 18. Rxd2 Rad8
19. Rxd8 Rxd8 20. Bf3 Rc8 21. Bxc6 Rxc6 22. Rb3 Rxc4 23. Rxb7 {with a stable
advantage in the endgame. It's basically a play for two results. Either Black
will hold, or he won't.} *

