1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 a5 5. g3 b6 {In this line Black plays a
hybrid of Bogo-Indian and Queen's Indian defense. The light-squared bishop
will be developed on b7 and it will become a worthy opponent of white's
fianchettoed bishop. In this scheme, however, the usefulness of the move a7-a5
is not entirely clear.} 6. Bg2 Bb7 (6... Ba6 7. Ne5 Ra7 (7... Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 Ra7
9. Nc3 $14) 8. Bxb4 axb4 9. a3 Bc8 10. Nd3 $14) ({In case of} 6... O-O {
White gets an additional option:} 7. Ne5 (7. O-O Bb7 {would transpose to the
main line.}) 7... Ra7 8. O-O d6 9. Nd3 Bxd2 10. Qxd2 {with a slight advantage.}
) 7. O-O O-O (7... Bxd2 8. Qxd2 {leads to a typical position structure for
Queen's Indian defense. White is slightly better thanks to his space advantage.
However, the only way to increase his advantage is to perform the advance
e2-e4 and this is far from easy. The game can develop as follows:} O-O 9. Nc3
Ne4 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Qf4 f5 (11... d5 12. Rac1 $14) 12. Rfd1 $14) 8. Bf4 (8.
Bg5 {is another option, but might lead to massive exchanges and equality. For
instanse:} Be7 9. Nc3 Ne4 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Qc2 Nxc3 12. Qxc3 d6 13. Nd2 Bxg2
14. Kxg2 e5 $11 {1-0 (37) Gleizerov,E (2566)-Fedorchuk,S (2634) Jurmala 2012})
(8. Nc3 d6 (8... Ne4 9. Qc2 Nxd2 (9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Nxc3 11. Qxc3 Be4 12. Nh4
Bxg2 13. Nxg2 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) 10. Nxd2 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 $14) 9. d5 $1 {
I like this idea as well.} exd5 (9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 exd5 11. Nh4 Ne4 12. Rc1
Nxc3 (12... dxc4 $4 13. Bxe4 Bxe4 14. Qd4 $18 {[%csl Re4,Rg7]}) 13. Rxc3 Na6
14. cxd5 $14 {The black knight will be well placed on c5, but white's space
advantage is a more important factor.}) 10. Nxd5 Bxd2 11. Qxd2 Nbd7 12. Nd4 $14
{1-0 (42) Romanov,E (2635)-Iordachescu,V (2581) Kishinev 2016}) 8... Be7 {
The bishop has to retreat, since White was threatening c4-c5, followed by
a2-a3, trapping the bishop.} 9. Nc3 Ne4 {A standart and the best reply. The
main fight in this type of position is around the key e4 square.} 10. Qc2 Nxc3
11. Qxc3 d6 12. Rfe1 Nd7 ({In case of} 12... Be4 {White should kick away
black's bishop by} 13. Qe3 Bb7 (13... f5 $2 {falls to} 14. Ng5 {[%csl Re6] and
Black is losing a pawn after} Bxg5 15. Bxg5 {followed by 16.Bxe4.}) 14. Qd3 {
preparing e2-e4.}) 13. Qc2 (13. e4 $6 {is too early and would be met by an
unpleasant counterstrike in the center:} e5 $1 14. Bd2 (14. dxe5 $6 dxe5 15.
Nxe5 $6 Bb4 {losing an exchange.}) 14... exd4 15. Nxd4 Bf6 {White's pieces are
awkwardly placed. Now he should go for a breakthrough:} 16. e5 $1 dxe5 17. Ne6
fxe6 18. Bxb7 Rb8 19. Be4 {and this position is approximately balanced.}) 13...
Ra7 (13... c5 14. d5 $1 (14. Rad1 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Rc8 17. Nb5 d5
18. b3 Bb4 $11) 14... exd5 (14... e5 15. Bd2 $14) 15. cxd5 b5 (15... Bxd5 $6
16. Rad1 Bb7 17. Bxd6 $16) 16. e4 {The structure is now more similar to Benoni
opening. I prefer white's chances. He can perform the e4-e5 breakthrough
sooner or later.}) 14. Rad1 (14. e4 $14) 14... Qa8 15. e4 {White seized more
space and has a stable advantage, which he, however, spoiled and eventually
lost in the game 0-1 (68) Van Wely, L (2675)-David, A (2567) Achaea 2017.} *

