1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 a5 5. g3 d5 {In this line Black is
playing through the center at an early stage.} 6. Qc2 (6. Bg2 dxc4 {would lead
to a Catalan opening, which is a different story.}) 6... O-O (6... c5 7. cxd5
cxd4 8. Nxd4 O-O 9. Bg2 {would transpose to the same position by different
order of moves.}) (6... Nc6 7. Bg2 dxc4 8. Qxc4 Qd5 9. Qd3 Qe4 {Black has to
insist on queens exchange, otherwise, the queen on d5 will not feel comfortable.
} 10. Qxe4 Nxe4 11. a3 Nxd2 12. Nbxd2 Be7 13. O-O {White achieved a pleasant
position in the correspondence game ½-½ (36) Baklanov, V (2461)-Pawlowski, S 
(2458) ICCF email 2008}) 7. Bg2 c5 (7... Nc6 {appeared in numerous games, but
blocking its' own "c" pawn is not necessarily a good idea.} 8. O-O Ne4 9. e3
$14) (7... c6 {is a solid and reliable option. The position might transpose to
a slightly inferior version of Catalan opening for Black, since the move a7-a5
usually, makes more sense after White has already b2-b3. But, here White
doesn't have to play b2-b3. The game may continue by} 8. O-O Be7 9. Bf4 Nbd7
10. Rd1 {with a long, manoeuvering battle ahead. I shall mention a small trap
that took place in one of my games. After} h6 (10... Nh5 11. Bc1 f5 {is an
attempt to transpose into Stonewall} (11... b5 {is an interesting try} 12. cxd5
(12. c5 $6 {is a mistake here. When the queenside is closed, Black can start
his own counterplay on the kingside.} f5 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 g5 {0-1 (43)
Xiong,J (2658)-Fedoseev,V (2703) Khanty-Mansiysk 2017}) 12... cxd5 13. e4 dxe4
14. Qxe4 Rb8 15. Ne5 (15. Qe2 {Kramnik played this move and win a beautiful
game. 1-0 (43) Kramnik,V (2743)-Topalov,V (2813) Elista 2006} Nhf6 16. Bf4 Rb6
17. Ne5 Nd5 18. Bxd5 exd5 19. Nc3 Nf6 (19... Nxe5 $1 {was Topalov's
improvement. The idea is beautiful.} 20. dxe5 d4 21. Be3 dxe3 {and it looks
like that Black has very nice positional compensation for the sacrificing
queen.}) 20. Nxb5 {1-0 (43) Kramnik,V (2743)-Topalov,V (2813) Elista 2006 With
an advantage for White.}) 15... Nhf6 16. Qc2 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nd7 18. Nc3 {
White's play looks easier. 1-0 (41) Markus, R (2625)-Dorfanis, I (2183) Skopje
2012}) 12. Nc3 Bd6 13. Bg5 $1 {White is winning an important tempo to play
e2-e3.} Qe8 14. e3 h6 15. Bf4 {White is definitely better here. If black take
on f4 than exf4 and Black's pawn on e6 will be a target. White also has a plan
to play on the queenside where the insert of a7-a5 looks in White's favor.} Be7
16. Ne2 Nhf6 17. Bc7 g5 18. Ne5 {White has an advantage here. 0-1 (49) Rahman,
Z (2513)-Adhiban,B (2609) Sharjah 2014}) 11. cxd5 ({Another option is:} 11. Nc3
dxc4 12. Nd2 Nb6 13. e4 {sacrificing a pawn, but seizing space in the center,
as in the game ½-½ (44) Wojtaszek, R (2713)-Gajewski, G (2629) Warsaw 2014})
11... exd5 12. Nc3 {the seemingly logical} Re8 $2 {falls to} 13. Nb5 $1 {
Black can't take the knight in view of 14.Bc7, trapping the queen. In the game
1-0 (37) Postny, E (2634)-Stocek, J (2567) Teplice 2015 the rook had to retreat
to e8 and I managed to convert my advantage successfully.}) ({In case of} 7...
b6 {White should continue by} 8. O-O Bb7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bf4 {pressing on the
c7 pawn, later by placing the rook on c1 as well.}) (7... dxc4 {is also
inaccurate. After} 8. Qxc4 {White is getting a good version of the Catalan
type position.}) (7... Be7 {is a possible move and after} 8. O-O c6 {will
transpose to the 7...c6 variation, mentioned above.}) 8. cxd5 (8. dxc5 d4 {
is black's idea. After} 9. Bxb4 axb4 {He will support his d4 and b4 pawns by
Nb8-c6 and get an adequate counterplay.}) 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Qb6 (9... Nxd5 10.
O-O {with a typical a-la Catalan slight advantage for White thanks to the great
bishop on g2, which exerts pressure on Black's queenside.}) 10. e3 exd5 11. O-O
Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 {Black doesn't have an isolated pawn anymore, but the c6
pawn can become a potential target.} 13. Bc3 {White achieved a slight
advantage in the game ½-½ (17) Krivoshey, S (2500)-Delchev, A (2656) Tarragona
2005} *

