1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 a5 5. g3 d6 6. Bg2 Nbd7 (6... Nc6 7. O-O
e5 8. Bg5 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ga2a3]} exd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6
12. Qxf6 gxf6 {In this endgame Black has a pair of good bishops, but his
structure is permanently damaged.} 13. a3 Bc5 14. Nc3 c6 15. e3 (15. Rac1 Be6
16. Ne4 Ke7 17. Rfd1 Rhd8 18. e3 $14 {1-0 (31) Postny,E (2649)-Riff,J (2487)
Evry 2008}) 15... Ke7 16. Na4 h5 17. h4 Rg8 18. Rfc1 Ra7 19. Bf3 Bg4 20. Bxg4
Rxg4 21. Kf1 $16 {1-0 (51) Giri,A (2714)-Ivanchuk,V (2775) Reggio Emilia 2012})
7. O-O e5 8. Be3 $1 {In my opinion, the most challenging move. In general, it
makes sense to move the bishop in order to create a threat a2-a3, but where to
move it? Back to c1 is strange; forward to g5 is okay, but the bishop will be
kicked away by h7-h6 at some point. So, e3 appears to be the most suitable
square. In fact, I learned about this move from Van Wely's games, so I was
curious to see if Loek can deal with his own pet line.} (8. Nc3 {used to be
the main choice, but after} O-O 9. Qc2 Re8 10. e4 exd4 11. Nxd4 Ne5 {Black
gets a decent piece play.}) 8... O-O (8... exd4 9. Bxd4 O-O 10. Qc2 {would
lead to the same position.}) 9. Qc2 (9. a3 exd4 10. Bxd4 Bc5 11. Nc3 Re8 12.
Qc2 (12. b3 c6 13. h3 Qe7 14. Ra2 h6 15. Kh2 (15. e4 $1 $14) 15... Ne5 16. Bxc5
dxc5 17. Qc1 Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 Bf5 19. e4 Bg6 $13 {1/2-1/2 (47) Van Wely,L (2654)
-Vitiugov,N (2742) Dubai 2014}) 12... c6 13. Rfd1 Qe7 14. h3 Ne5 15. Bxc5 Nxf3+
16. Bxf3 dxc5 17. Bg2 Qe5 18. e4 g5 19. Qd2 $14 {1/2-1/2 (67) Van Wely,L (2679)
-Nakamura,H (2769) Wijk aan Zee 2013}) 9... exd4 10. Bxd4 Re8 11. Nc3 c6 12.
Rad1 Qe7 13. a3 Bc5 14. Rfe1 {Both sides make useful moves. White is ready to
push e2-e4, seizing more space.} h6 15. e4 Bxd4 16. Nxd4 {White has small, but
stable edge thanks to space superiority - ½-½ (70) Postny, E (2616)-Van Wely,
L (2685) Novi Sad 2016} *

