1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Bxd2+ {This exchange used to
be a sideline, but gained popularity a few years ago thanks to efforts of
Croatian GM Mladen Palac, among others.} ({The move} 5... b6 {will turn the
game into one of the sidelines of Queen's Indian. After} 6. Bg2 Bb7 7. O-O
Bxd2 {I recommend the queen recapture:} 8. Qxd2 {and then to develop the
knight on c3. White achieves a slight advantage thanks to space superiority.
Later on, he should prepare the advance e2-e4 and/or d4-d5, grabbing more space.
}) 6. Qxd2 (6. Nbxd2 {is a concession, as white's knight is passive on d2. It
should be developed on c3. Black has no problems after} d6 {followed by e6-e5
at some point, as typical for Bogo-Indian defense.}) 6... Nc6 (6... d6 7. Bg2
O-O 8. Nc3 e5 9. O-O {This is the ideal setup for White against the
Bogo-Indian. All his pieces are developed on their best squares and his space
advantage is indisputable.} Re8 ({In case of careless} 9... e4 $2 10. Ng5 Bf5
11. Qf4 {[%csl Re4,Rf5] Black will simply lose his central pawn.}) 10. e4 $14)
(6... O-O 7. Bg2 d6 8. Nc3 {Will transpose to the above-mentioned line 6...d6
by a different order of moves.}) (6... d5 {is a playable move. After} 7. Bg2 O-O
8. O-O {the position is similar to a Catalan setup, just the dark-squared
bishops are already swapped. For instance, after} Rd8 {the most flexible way
of development is} 9. Rc1 {Later on White can move his queen to e3 or even f4
and develop his queenside knight to d2. White's advantage is marginal.}) (6...
Ne4 $6 {is a dubious jump.} 7. Qc2 f5 (7... Qb4+ $6 8. Nbd2 Nxd2 9. Nxd2 {
and Black basically just lost few tempos in the opening. His kingside made
three moves and got exchanged. The queen will also have to retreat soon.}) (
7... d5 8. Bg2 $14) 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O $14 {followed by 10.Nc3.}) 7. b3 $1 {
Not an obvious move, but appears to be the most challenging one. At first
sight, it looks weird to play such non-developing move, protecting the c4 pawn,
before Black has even played d7-d5. In order to understand the subtleties
better, let's check the alternatives.} (7. Bg2 $6 {allows an unpleasant check
after} Ne4 8. Qc2 Qb4+ {Now White faces an unpleasant choice:} 9. Nbd2 (9. Kf1
{is possible, but losing the right to castle at such an early stage is not
recommended. Black is doing well after} d5) (9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 11.
bxc3 {leads to an endgame, where only black's position can be preferred thanks
to a superior pawn structure.}) 9... Nxd2 10. Qxd2 Qxc4 {losing a pawn for a
murky compensation.}) (7. Nc3 d5 8. b3 O-O 9. Bg2 dxc4 10. bxc4 Rd8 11. e3 e5
$6 ({Black shall improve by} 11... Rb8 {followed by 12...b6 and 13...Bb7.}) 12.
Nd5 $1 Qd6 (12... Nxd5 13. cxd5 Rxd5 $2 14. Nxe5 $16) 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Nxe5
Nxe5 15. dxe5 Rxd2 16. exf6 Rc2 17. O-O Rxc4 18. Rfd1 $14 {1-0 (57) Postny,E 
(2641)-Socko,B (2622) Porto Rio 2014}) 7... d5 (7... O-O 8. Bg2 Ne4 9. Qb2 f5
10. O-O d6 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. Qxc3 e5 13. e3 Bd7 14. b4 Rae8 (14... e4 15. Nd2 {
white's chances are preferable. His play on the queenside is easy, white it's
hard for Black to create something tangible on the kingside.}) 15. Rfe1 $6 ({
My play had to be more concrete:} 15. b5 Nd8 16. Qa5 {attacking pawns on the
queenside.}) 15... Nd8 16. b5 g5 17. dxe5 $6 ({Again, I missed a chance for} 
17. Qa5) 17... dxe5 18. Rad1 Nf7 $13 {1/2-1/2 (23) Postny,E (2625)-Kelires,A 
(2464) Kavala 2016}) 8. Bg2 O-O (8... Ne4 9. Qb2 Qb4+ 10. Nfd2 Nxd2 11. Nxd2
$14 {1-0 (66) Vidit,S (2670)-Safarli,E (2680) Dubai 2017}) 9. O-O Rd8 (9...
dxc4 10. bxc4 Rd8 11. Qb2 Rb8 12. Nbd2 {and I achieved a pleasant position in
the game 1-0 (61) Postny,E (2635)-Brkic,A (2603) Zadar 2014}) 10. Qb2 $1 {
Somewhat amusing "queen fianchetto" is one of the points of the subtle move 7.
b3. Moving the queen away from the x-ray of black's rook. At the same time
White keeps his center intact.} a5 (10... b6 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Rac1 Ne4 13. Rfd1
Rab8 14. cxd5 exd5 15. a3 a5 16. e3 $14 {White's further plan shall include
doubling the rooks along the "c" file, as in the game 1-0 (55) Lupulescu,C 
(2631)-Papaioannou,I (2638) Reykjavik 2015}) 11. a3 b6 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Rc1
Bb7 14. Nc3 Na7 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 $14 {1-0 (37) Rodshtein,M (2654)-Ortiz
Suarez,I (2625) Tsaghkadzor 2015} *

