1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Nc3 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 {
Here we get to, what used to be the main line. Black gave his dark-squared
bishop, but will swap white's bishop for a knight as well so that White won't
have a pair of bishops.} 8. Rc1 {The most challenging move.} ({White gets very
little after} 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 Qb4) 8... O-O 9. Bg2 d6 10. d5 (10. O-O Nxc3
11. Rxc3 e5 12. d5 Nb8 {appeared in numerous games and the verdict here is
that Black is okay. White does have more space, but his bishop is restricted
by his own d5 pawn.}) 10... Nxc3 (10... Nd8 11. O-O Nxc3 12. Rxc3 {would
transpose, by different order of moves, to the line, examined below.}) 11. Rxc3
Nb8 (11... Nd8 {is possible, but here the knight has fewer possibilities, as it
is restricted by the d5 pawn.} 12. O-O e5 13. c5 $1 dxc5 14. Qc2 e4 (14... b6
15. Re3 f6 16. Nxe5 $1 fxe5 17. d6 cxd6 18. Bxa8 {wins an exchange.}) 15. Ne1
f5 16. f3 $1 {The c5 pawn won't run, while it's important to undermine black's
pawns chain.} exf3 17. Bxf3 $14 {1-0 (57) Eljanov,P (2681)-Jones,G (2641)
Reykjavik 2013}) 12. dxe6 $1 {White gives part of his space advantage, but
opens the long diagonal for his bishop.} (12. O-O e5 {transposes to the line,
mentioned above - 10.0-0.}) 12... fxe6 {Now Black has more central pawns, but
every advance will weaken some squares. For instance: e6-e5 will weaken the d5
square, and if Black will cover it by c7-c6, then the d6 pawn will become a
target.} (12... Bxe6 13. Nd4 $14) 13. O-O Nd7 {The best way to develop the
pieces. The alternatives are worse.} (13... Nc6 $6 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 {
After the exchange of knights, it will be more difficult for Black to complete
the development of the queenside. For instance:} e5 16. Qd2 Rb8 17. c5 $1 {
ruining black's structure.}) ({Similar idea works after} 13... a5 $6 14. c5 $1
dxc5 15. Ne5 Nd7 16. Nxd7 Bxd7 17. Qc2 {White gets the pawn on c5 and will
exert a serious pressure against black's weaknesses.}) 14. Nd4 (14. Qd2 Nf6 15.
Ng5 h6 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 {The exchange of knights didn't make black's life
easy. White's pieces are more active and black's king is slightly more
vulnerable than his counterpart.} Rb8 18. c5 dxc5 19. Rfc1 b6 20. b4 Bb7 21.
Bxb7 Rxb7 22. bxc5 $14 {1/2-1/2 (59) Postny,E (2648)-Chernuschevich,A (2501)
Nancy 2010}) 14... Nf6 (14... c6 15. e4 {I like this idea even more than the
more common 15.b4.} (15. b4 e5 16. Nc2 {appeared in several games and was
sufficient for a slight advantage as well.}) 15... Nf6 16. Rd3 {The d6 pawn is
a long-term target.} e5 17. Ne2 (17. Nc2 Be6 18. Ne3 {is more precise. The
knight is ideally placed on e3, covering important d5, f5, and g4 squares.})
17... Be6 ({Here Black could play} 17... Bg4 $1 {to provoke an f2-f3, which
would be a slight concession.}) 18. b3 Rad8 19. Nc3 $14 {1-0 (57) Epishin,V 
(2557)-Barbier,S (2149) Ghent 2016}) 15. Qd2 e5 16. Nc2 Be6 17. Ne3 {White has
a slight edge. His pieces are well placed and he can exert pressure on the
queenside - ½-½ (43) Markus, R (2662)-Popov, S (2447) Kragujevac 2016} *

